# Keep documentation updated

After any change that affects behavior, CLI, config, architecture, or protocol, update the docs in the same change. Do not leave documentation for a follow-up.

## What to update

| Change type | Update |
|-------------|--------|
| User-facing CLI, install, usage, features, env vars | Root [README.md](README.md) |
| Process model, session layout, modules, attach/detach | [docs/DESIGN.md](docs/DESIGN.md) |
| Socket framing / client–server messages | [docs/PROTOCOL.md](docs/PROTOCOL.md) |
| New or renamed design doc | Index table in [docs/README.md](docs/README.md) |

## Rules

- Prefer editing existing docs over adding new files. Add a new doc only when the topic does not fit `DESIGN.md` or `PROTOCOL.md`.
- Keep README user-facing: install, commands, detach key, session dir. Put internals in `docs/` (`DESIGN.md`, `PROTOCOL.md`, …).
- If a change makes a documented claim false (flags, defaults, paths, protocol fields), fix that claim in the same edit.
- Pure refactors with no behavioral or interface change need no doc update — say so briefly if asked.
- Do not invent features in docs that are not implemented.
